From Subject Re Barbecued foods and health risk In article SFEGUS wrote In article Mark Robert Thorson writes An odd exception to the rule seems to be the product known as gumbo file' This is nothing more than coarsely ground dried sassafras This is not only a natural product but a natural product still in its natural form so maybe that's how they evade Or maybe a special exemption was made to appease powerful Louisiana One possible reason is that file' is made with sassafras leaves while root beer was made with sassafras bark or root The leaves contain either no or less saffrole than the There is also some sort of treatment which putatively removes saffrole from sassafras I have some concentrated sassafras tea extract which is claimed to have the saffrole I think what we have to keep in mind is that even though it may be illegal to commercially produce sell food with carcinogenic substances it is not illegal for people to do such to their own food smoking etc Is this true Well the last time that I went to the store to buy sassafras bark to make root beer there was a sign saying that it wasn't sold for human Also when I asked the person if they had wild cherry bark and wintergreen bark she made a point of telling me that I couldn't buy sassafras for human I find the fact that some people reckless enough to step into an automobile live in fear of dropping dead because of a pork rib quite funny in a sick Eric Pepke INTERNET Supercomputer Computations Research Institute MFENET pepke fsu Florida State University SPAN scri pepke Tallahassee FL BITNET pepke fsu Disclaimer My employers seldom even LISTEN to my Meta disclaimer Any society that needs disclaimers has too many